File: Minister of Employment and Labour Thulas Nxesi. AFP/Glyn Kirk JOHANNESBURG - Labour Minister Thulas Nxesi says companies are still not paying their workers minimum wage, despite mandatory changes and increases over the past year. Nxesi was responding to a written parliamentary Q and A. READ: Nxesi announces new minimum wage for SA He reveals that approximately 36 percent of all workers are paid below the national minimum wage. Nxesi clarified that the legislated minimum wage is not R3,500 per month as is widely reported. Instead, it is R23.19 per hour payable for the numbers of ordinary hours worked.